kfactory subprocess-delegated token refresh (deployment glue).

Layered on top of the upstreamable bearer/workspace/routing patch.
NOT upstreamable: this contains kfactory-specific paths, exit-code
conventions, and a shared file-cache schema between Go (kfactory) and
TypeScript (opencode TUI). See docs/spec.md in the kfactory repo for
the wider design.

What this adds:
  - `OPENCODE_SERVER_BEARER_CACHE_PATH` env (core/flag/flag.ts) +
    `bearerFromCache()` in server/auth.ts. When set, server-side
    `ServerAuth.header()` reads the access token from the cache file
    if neither `credentials.bearer` nor `OPENCODE_SERVER_BEARER` is
    supplied -- matters because kfactory rotates the token between
    the launcher's exec and the SDK's first request.
  - `createBearerRefreshFetch` in cli/cmd/tui/attach.ts: a custom fetch
    that reads the cache file on every request and spawns
    `kfactory auth refresh` (subprocess) when the access token is
    near expiry. kfactory owns the lockfile + IdP HTTP + atomic
    rename; the TUI just reads the resulting file.
  - Exit-code contract with the Go side: 0 = ok, 1 = not_logged_in,
    2 = other error. See KFACTORY_EXIT_* consts inline + the
    authoritative definitions in kfactory's cmd/kfactory/exit.go.
  - Schema-versioned auth.json read: TUI asserts schema_version on
    every refresh.
  - `onBearerRefreshHint` channel + a toast subscription in app.tsx
    that surfaces a one-time hint to the operator (`not_logged_in` /
    `spawn_error` / `other_error`).

kfactory must be on the operator's PATH for the subprocess refresh to
work. Same-machine, same-UID, same-auth.json.

